ention of Instructors of the Deaf in Milan, published his 'impressions' that questioned the majority's passage of a strict oralism agenda. In 1908, Thomas Flowers wrote 'I was a little human plant,' a paean to education without irony despite the concurrent policy banning African Americans from attending Gallaudet College. These and a host of other Deaf writers--Laurent Clerc, Kate Farlow, Edmund Booth, Laura Redden Searing, Freda W. Bauman, Vera Gammon, Isaac H. Benedict, James Nack, John Carlin, Joseph Mount and many more--reveal the vitality and resilience of Deaf writers in an era of wrenching change"--cProject Muse website.uhttp://muse.jhu.edu/books/9781563685668/  aIncludes bibliographical references. 0aDeaf, Writings of the, American. 0aAmerican prose literaturey20th century. 0aAmerican prose literaturey19th century. 0aAmerican literaturey20th century. 0aAmerican literaturey19th century. 0aDeaf authors. 7aKurzgeschichte.0(DE-588)4033842-32gnd 7aAmerikanisches Englisch.0(DE-588)4094804-32gnd 7aGehoÌˆrlosigkeit.0(DE-588)4059132-32gnd 7aUSA.0(DE-588)4078704-72gnd 7a1830 - 19302fast 0aProse literature. 7aLiterature.2lcgft1 aNelson, Jennifer L.,d1965-eeditor.1 aHarmon, Kristen,eeditor. 0aGallaudet deaf literature series ;vv. 2.  aBrodartbBRODn106067834  aBaker and TaylorbBTCPnBK0013009873  aYBP Library ServicesbYANKn10390200  aCoutts Information ServicesbCOUTn25246964  aC0bWAU